<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
If you are citing a work which has no author, if the title is long, the first few words of the title 
should be used. Use double quotation marks around the title of an article and capitalise using title 
case (the first letter of each major word is capitalised), even though sentence case (the first letter 
of the first word only, in the main title and subtitle, is capitalised) is used in the reference list. 
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	The author&#8217;s report &#34;Hong Kong Braces for Protests&#34; (2017) revealed that&hellip;
	<br>
	Alternatively: &hellip;revealed the author&#8217;s report (&#34;Hong Kong Braces for Protests&#34;, 
	2017).
</blockquote>
<br>
If you are using a direct quotation, consisting of fewer than 40 words, enclose the quote using 
double quotation marks and include page numbers.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	A <em>Melbourne Herald</em> report &#45; &#34;Hong Kong Braces for Protests&#34; (2017) &#45; 
	revealed that &#34;rubbish collection is costing the country millions&#34; (p. A5).
	<br>
	Alternatively: &#34;Rubbish collection is costing the country millions&#34; 
	(&#34;Hong Kong Braces for Protests&#34;, 2017, p. A5).
</blockquote>
<br>
If the quotation is greater than 40 words, the quote is displayed in a double spaced, indented 
block at 1.27cm from the left margin. Do not use double quotation marks to enclose a block quotation.
